<HEAD>20th Anniversary of Lunar Landing Brings Call for New Adventures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Apollo-Footprints on Moon, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Four days...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with description
of celebration. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Aldrin, who...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WHUN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after man walked on the
moon, those responsible for that ``one giant leap for mankind'' said
the space program needs another bold challenge to recapture
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s imagination.
   And with <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s imagination, they said, will come the
financial support needed for a daring project, such as landing
astronauts on Mars.
   On <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, a soldout crowd of more than 4,000 people joined the
Apollo 11 crew _ <PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON>, <PERSON>Edwin</PERSON> ``Buzz'' <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Michael
Collins</PERSON> _ at the <LOCATION>Alabama Space</LOCATION> and Rocket Center for the first of
four celebrations around the country to commemorate the lunar
landing on <DATE>July 20, 1969</DATE>.
   Huntsville's celebration focuses on the role this northern
<LOCATION>Alabama</LOCATION> city and the <PERSON>Wernher von Braun</PERSON> rocket team at <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s
<ORGANIZATION>Marshall Space Flight Center</ORGANIZATION> played in developing the <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> V
rocket to propel Apollo 11 on its journey to the moon.
   The celebration was like a high-tech rock concert without the
music. Lasers bounced off rockets exhibited throughout the center,
sound effects simulated the takeoff of the <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> V rocket to the
moon, and actors portrayed <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION>'s and <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON>'s walk on the
rugged lunar landscape four days after blasting off from <ORGANIZATION>Kennedy
Space Center</ORGANIZATION>.
   It climaxed with the Apollo 11 crew rising from a cloud of smoke
20 feet into the air to the front of a giant movie screen showing
footage of their travels. The crew was surrounded by a cacophony of
fireworks and dozens of dancing laser beams.
   Aldrin, who spent much of his time in <LOCATION>Huntsville</LOCATION> autographing his
new book ``Men from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>,'' describes the 20th anniversary as
``bittersweet.'' That's because he worries that <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> ``will sink
to second-rate status'' in space if it continues on its present
course.
   The 59-year-old former astronaut said <DATE>Saturday</DATE> he hoped the
anniversary would help <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> set well-defined space objectives
instead of having each space shuttle flight ``being an entity into
itself.''
   ``There is an excitement about the past but there is not an
awareness of where we want to go,'' he said in an interview.
   He envisions the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> working with the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> on space research projects, with a goal of developing
spaceships that will take advantage of planetary movements to
slingshot between Mars and <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> on five-month cycles.
   <PERSON>Collins</PERSON>, 58, also called for greater direction in the space
program.
   ``One of these days, and I hope it's not too long, this country
is going to decide it wants to go to Mars,'' he told a gathering of
engineers who worked on the Apollo project.
   Armstrong, 58, told the same group, ``A machine is man-made and
hence imperfect. No one has ever made a perfect machine. Those of
you who made the <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> V came about as close as history ever
recorded.''
   <PERSON>Jack Lee</PERSON>, director at <ORGANIZATION>Marshall Space Flight Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Huntsville</LOCATION>
and a former member of the von <PERSON>Braun</PERSON> team, vividly remembers
President <PERSON>Kennedy</PERSON>'s seemingly impossible challenge to land a man on
the moon by the end of the <DATE>1960s</DATE>.
   No president has issued an equally bold challenge since then, but
he hopes President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> will in a 20th anniversary speech <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   ``We must continue what <PERSON>Wernher von Braun</PERSON> and Apollo 11 started
many years ago, that is to reach out and touch another world,'' he
said. ``This time our launching pad is going to be the space
station.''
   <PERSON>Konrad Dannenberg</PERSON>, a German rocket scientist who came to <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>
with <PERSON>Von Braun</PERSON> after World War II and later supervised engineering
and testing of the <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> rocket, said the moon landing ``was the
biggest step for mankind that has ever taken place. I hope this
(anniversary) is the first step toward an even bigger achievement.''
   <PERSON>Ed Buckbee</PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION>Space and Rocket Center</ORGANIZATION>, a tourist
attraction focused on space achievements, and a former member of <PERSON>Von
Braun</PERSON>'s staff, said he hopes ``President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> gives us a goal. I've
heard everything from a moon colony to a man on <ORGANIZATION>Mars</ORGANIZATION>, with a space
plane in there.''
   Buckbee said he sees only one way for <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> to recapture <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s
imagination and pocketbook.
   ``It's got to be a man on Mars landing,'' he said. ``I don't
think a space station is going to capture American imagination. It's
got to be something that puts man and machine against the hazards of
space.''
</TEXT>
