<HEAD>What Happened 20 Years Ago During Moon Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of events on the
Apollo 11 moon flight <DATE>20 years ago today</DATE>:
   As Apollo 11 coasted smoothly toward the moon, astronauts <PERSON>Neil
Armstrong</PERSON> and <PERSON>Buzz Aldrin</PERSON> left <PERSON>Mike Collins</PERSON> alone in the command
module <ORGANIZATION>Columbia</ORGANIZATION> and crawled through a connecting tunnel to enter the
lunar module <ORGANIZATION>Eagle</ORGANIZATION>. With earthlings watching on television,
<ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> inspected the craft and checked switch settings
to make certain nothing had been disturbed or damaged by buffeting
at the time of launch. They reported the lunar ship was in good
shape.
   At <TIME>11:32 p.m. EDT</TIME>, the astronauts passed through an area called
the equigravisphere, a ``twilight zone'' in which the gravitational
influence of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and moon is about equal. Once through this
zone, the moon won the gravitational tug-of-war and Apollo 11 was in
the grip of lunar gravity. The ship passed through this invisible
barrier when it was 43,495 miles from the moon and 214,402 miles
from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
