<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Astronauts Put Moon, Va., On The Map</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city that <PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON> and <PERSON>Edwin</PERSON> ``Buzz''
<PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> put on the map 20 years ago planned no official festivities
to mark the 20th anniversary of the astronauts' moon walk.
   Residents there are still trying to explain where they live.
   Before the moon walk, <PERSON>Moon</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Va.</LOCATION>, was little more than a post
office and a bump in the road in <LOCATION>Mathews County</LOCATION> near the <LOCATION>Chesapeake
Bay</LOCATION>.
   You couldn't even find Moon on a <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION> road map.
   Today, the community of about 100 families isn't much bigger,
but at least it's on the map. The attention <PERSON>Moon</PERSON> attracted in <DATE>1969</DATE>
when the Eagle landed on its celestial cousin apparently encouraged
the <ORGANIZATION>Virginia Department of Transportation</ORGANIZATION> to put it on the official
state map.
   Sometimes, even maps don't help.
   <PERSON>Pat Chalkley</PERSON>, a former <LOCATION>Mechanicsville</LOCATION> resident and relative
newcomer to <PERSON>Moon</PERSON>, said she sent her new address to a friend, who
replied with a note: ``Where in the hell is Moon?''
   Almost heaven, to hear <PERSON>Mrs. Chalkley</PERSON> and others describe their
community.
   ``I've heard people say that once you've seen a full moon over
the <LOCATION>Chesapeake Bay</LOCATION>, you never want to leave,'' said <PERSON>Mrs. Chalkley</PERSON>,
whose husband, <PERSON>Blanton</PERSON>, commutes 90 minutes to <LOCATION>Richmond</LOCATION> to work.
``I was sitting there the other night, looked up and saw this
absolutely gorgeous big ol' orange moon.''
 
</TEXT>
