<HEAD>First American in Space Opposes Joint Soviet Missions; Rocket Scientists
Meet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto HON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's first astronaut in the <DATE>1960s</DATE>
space race with the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> opposes joint missions today, but
not for political reasons.
   ``I think it would be a step backwards to go that route,'' <PERSON>Alan
Shepard</PERSON> said <DATE>Monday</DATE> during a visit to the Space and <ORGANIZATION>Rocket Center
for Space Celebration</ORGANIZATION> '89 festivities. ``I would rather see us
develop the technology to have planetary travel _ manned and
unmanned.''
   A separate celebration of the 20th anniversary of the <DATE>1969</DATE> moon
walk, meanwhile, included some bitterness.
   About 40 aging German rocket scientists who helped build
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s space program expressed disappointment that one of their
brethren was not present for a reunion of the 20th anniversary
celebration of Americans landing on the moon.
   <PERSON>Arthur Rudolph</PERSON>, project manager for the <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> 5 rocket at the
<ORGANIZATION>Marshall Space Flight Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Huntsville</LOCATION>, remained in voluntary
exile in his native <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, under threat of prosecution for
alleged Nazi war crimes if he returned to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   ``It's a shame for the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to send out a man who did so
much for the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>,'' said scientist <PERSON>Konrad Dannenberg</PERSON>.
``Everyone here should be ashamed this thing happened.''
   Rudolph, now 84, retired in <DATE>January 1970</DATE> after helping send two
spaceships to the moon and moved to <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, where he lived
in relative obscurity for 14 years.
   His tranquil retirement ended when the <ORGANIZATION>Justice Department's
Office of Special Investigations</ORGANIZATION> raised allegations that during
World War II he was involved in the deaths of thousands of
concentration camp prisoners who were forced to work in a V-2 rocket
factory where he was technical director. Those allegations were
backed up by some survivors.
   Rudolph left the country and returned to <LOCATION>Hamburg</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>,
where a two-year investigation found no offense against <PERSON>Rudolph</PERSON>. His
West German citizenship was returned.
   <PERSON>Shepard</PERSON>, one of 12 Americans to walk on the moon, disagreed with
Apollo 11 moonwalker <PERSON>Edwin</PERSON> ``Buzz'' <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON>, who said during a trip
to <LOCATION>Huntsville</LOCATION> <DATE>Saturday</DATE> that <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> should pursue joint missions
with the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> and possibly <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>.
   ``I think our space technology level, in general, is ahead of the
Soviets,'' <PERSON>Shepard</PERSON> said.
   Shepard, now 65, rode a Huntsville-built Redstone rocket into
space on <DATE>May 5, 1961</DATE>, as the American space program rushed to catch
the Soviets, who had sent <PERSON>Yuri Gagarin</PERSON> into space on <DATE>April 12</DATE>.
   He returned to space in <DATE>February 1971</DATE> on Apollo 14 and became the
fifth man to walk on the moon _ a feat never matched by the <LOCATION>Soviet
Union</LOCATION>. Shepard is now is a commercial real estate developer in
<LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>.
   Meanwhile, children who weren't alive when man first landed on
the moon got a chance to guide another ``spacecraft'' to a lunar
landing <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   Fifteen students worked at the <ORGANIZATION>Challenger Center</ORGANIZATION>'s mock <ORGANIZATION>Mission
Control</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, while another group of children were ``flying''
in a simulator at a second <ORGANIZATION>Challenger Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Greenbelt</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Md</LOCATION>. They
were helped by flight controllers who were in <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Mission Control</ORGANIZATION>
during Apollo 11's historic landing.
   The youths talked through headsets and completed checklists
before giving the go-ahead for the mock landing.
   The centers, built as a memorial to the seven astronauts who died
in the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger, offer youngsters a
chance to learn by participating in simulated missions.
</TEXT>
