<HEAD>Youths Honor Lunar Landing With Simulated Trip to Moon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Rocket Scientists, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children who weren't alive when man first landed
on the moon got a chance to guide another ``spacecraft'' to a lunar
landing <DATE>Monday</DATE> at the <ORGANIZATION>Challenger Center</ORGANIZATION>'s mock <ORGANIZATION>Mission Control</ORGANIZATION>.
   Aided by nine flight controllers who were in <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Mission
Control</ORGANIZATION> during Apollo 11's historic <DATE>July 1969</DATE> landing, the youths
talked through headsets and completed checklists before giving the
go-ahead for the mock landing.
   While the 15 students worked in <ORGANIZATION>Mission Control</ORGANIZATION>, another group of
children were ``flying'' in a simulator at a second <ORGANIZATION>Challenger
Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Greenbelt</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Md</LOCATION>. Accompanying those children was former
astronaut <PERSON>Michael Collins</PERSON>, who circled the moon in Apollo 11's
command module while <PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON> and <PERSON>Edwin</PERSON> ``Buzz'' <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> landed
in the lunar module.
   ``I learned what it really feels like, and what you have to do to
communicate with people up there. It's really kind of hard,'' said
<PERSON>Trina Jones</PERSON>, 11, who will attend <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Lanier Middle School</ORGANIZATION> this
<DATE>fall</DATE>.
   ``I was afraid I would mess up,'' she added.
   The simulation marked the first time that students from the two
<ORGANIZATION>Challenger Centers</ORGANIZATION> were able to communicate with each other. The
facility in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION> was the first center, opening in <DATE>August 1988</DATE>.
   The centers, built as a memorial to the seven astronauts who died
in the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger, offer youngsters a
chance to learn by participating in simulated missions. The two
centers are the first of a planned network of simulators.
   For about 30 minutes, the students sat behind their control
consoles along with the veteran flight controllers. The mostly
fourth-, fifth- and sixth-graders also watched three television
monitors above, which showed their counterparts working at the other
center and television footage taken when the real lunar module
approached the moon.
   Shortly before the landing, <PERSON>Gene Kranz</PERSON>, chief flight controller
for the touchdown <DATE>two decades ago</DATE>, asked all the controllers if they
were ``go, no-go'' for a landing. They all gave their OK.
   Soon, a voice from <LOCATION>Greenbelt</LOCATION> repeated the words spoken 20 years
ago: ``<LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>. Tranquillity base here. The <ORGANIZATION>Eagle</ORGANIZATION> has landed.''
   Several relatives of the Challenger astronauts attended the
event, including <PERSON>Jane Smith</PERSON>, widow of pilot <PERSON>Michael Smith</PERSON>; <PERSON>Lorna
Onizuka</PERSON>, widow of <PERSON>Ellison Onizuka</PERSON>; and <PERSON>Cheryl McNair</PERSON>, widow of <PERSON>Ron
McNair</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Kranz</PERSON>, who is now director of mission operations at the <ORGANIZATION>National
Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Johnson Space Center</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, said such simulations are important to keep children
interested in science and space so they may be motivated to pursue
careers in those areas.
   ``It's an incredible opportunity to basically challenge their
curiosity. If their curiosity is up, we'll do OK,'' <PERSON>Kranz</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
