<HEAD>Magazine Says Soviets Should Have Broadcast US Moon Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Soviet space writer said in an article
published <DATE>Monday</DATE> the <ORGANIZATION>Kremlin</ORGANIZATION> made a mistake by not broadcasting live
television coverage when the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Apollo 11 mission landed on the
moon <DATE>July 21, 1969</DATE>.
   ``Late on the <TIME>night</TIME> of <DATE>July 21, 1969</DATE>, on central television, if
my memory doesn't trick me, they broadcast the program, `Pages of a
Musical Spectacle,''' <PERSON>Yaroslav Golovanov</PERSON> wrote in this week's
edition of the magazine <ORGANIZATION>Ogonyok</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``At that same moment, all of mankind was holding its breath for
the first landing of man on the moon.''
   Soviet television carried extensive coverage of the linkup of the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Apollo and Soviet Soyuz capsules in <DATE>1975</DATE>, but largely ignored
the American program to land on the moon.
   By doing so, <PERSON>Golovanov</PERSON> wrote, ``we showed a lack of respect for
the astronauts, for that country ... and for ourselves. Our people
know about the Apollo program by hearsay, and are always amazed when
they hear that 12 men have landed on the moon.''
   ``It is never too late to correct a mistake. Today, 20 years
after the first steps on the moon, I want to recount the history of
Apollo 11 and its crew,'' <PERSON>Golovanov</PERSON> wrote in the first of a series
of articles to appear in <LOCATION>Ogonyok</LOCATION>. The magazine has been in the
forefront of glasnost, President <PERSON>Mikhail S. Gorbachev</PERSON>'s program of
greater openness.
   The article, illustrated with black-and-white photographs, gave
the biographies of the three crew members _ <PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON>, <PERSON>Edwin</PERSON>
``Buzz'' <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Michael Collins</PERSON> _ and described the flight of
the ``Eagle'' lunar landing module.
   The most dangerous moment of the flight, <PERSON>Golovanov</PERSON> wrote, came
when <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> took manual control of the module for the final
descent.
   With tens of millions of television viewers around the world
watching a live broadcast, <PERSON>Golovanov</PERSON> wrote, <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> set the craft
down safely and ``man had landed on the moon. A bold and ancient
dream had come true.''
   Ogonyok did not indicate the scope of the articles to follow.
</TEXT>
