<HEAD>Astronaut John W. Young Disappointed With Space Program Progress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former chief <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> astronaut says he is
disappointed in the progress of the nation's space program, blaming
the emphasis on the shuttle for a slowdown in space development and
exploration.
   The reusable orbiters on which <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> staked its future in the
early <DATE>1970s</DATE> have never been the workhorses their supporters
promised, says <PERSON>John W. Young</PERSON>.
   ``I think we were being unrealistic about what our capabilities
and limitations were in the old days,'' said <PERSON>Young</PERSON>, who flew on the
first manned Gemini mission in <DATE>1965</DATE>. ``It (the shuttle) just has to
have too much hands-on work done with it to make it do all the
things we wanted it to do.''
   Young, now a safety and engineering trouble-shooter for the
<ORGANIZATION>Johnson Space Center</ORGANIZATION>'s director, orbited the moon and explored its
surface during the Apollo era. He later commanded the first and
ninth shuttle flights.
   ``It is almost 20 years since we landed people on the moon,''
<PERSON>Young</PERSON> said. ``And if you had asked me after the moon landing what
we'd be doing in 20 years, I'd have said we'd have a base on the
moon in 20 years.''
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> sold the shuttle to <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> as a quickly refurbishable,
inexpensive-to-operate spacewagon.
   ``I never believed it could be that way,'' <PERSON>Young</PERSON> said. ``I
wasn't involved in selling it, but I was involved in the technical
details of helping design and build it, and it was too
complicated.''
   Young said the shuttle is capable of fulfilling its creators'
expectations, but tight budgets hurt it when <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> could not afford
to stockpile spare parts for quick repairs.
   Quick shuttle turnarounds and reflights and routine <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>
landings never panned out, nor is the shuttle an inexpensive way to
fly, he added. And the assumption that it pays to salvage and reuse
each <MONEY>$15 million</MONEY> solid fuel rocket booster casings may be wrong,
<PERSON>Young</PERSON> said.
   Delays in flights also affect <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s supply of flight-ready
astronauts. Fourteen astronauts who flew before the shuttle
Challenger exploded decided not to wait for flights to resume. The
space center has 93 astronauts left and is accepting applications
through <DATE>July 1</DATE> for a <DATE>1990</DATE> astronaut class.
   ``I expect there's a lot of astronauts leaving because they see
the line at the end of the tunnel _ the line they've got to stand
in to get a flight is so long.''
</TEXT>
