<FIRST>s a BC-Apollo-FootprintsForever Adv16   06-28 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Apollo-Footprints Forever, Adv 16,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Footprints Still on Windless, Rainless Moon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Part of an eight-story package for use at will or on successful
Sundays in July.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The footprints left in the lunar dust
20 years ago by Apollo 11 astronauts <PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON> and <PERSON>Buzz Aldrin</PERSON>
should be visible for half a million years because the moon has no
atmosphere to erode them, says a <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> chemist.
   But the absence of an atmosphere also leaves the moon unprotected
from meteorite and cosmic ray strikes, and these eventually will
erase the footprints, reports <PERSON>James R. Arnold</PERSON>.
   Arnold, who calls himself a cosmochemist, is director of the
<ORGANIZATION>California Space Institute</ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>San
Diego</LOCATION>.
   ``The moon is a quiet place, lacking an atmosphere, and is
therefore free of wind and rain,'' he said.
   Arnold and his colleagues have developed techniques to measure
the rate of erosion and turnover of rocks and soil on the moon by
studying radioactive isotopes in samples brought back from six
Apollo lunar landing missions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 16</NOTE>
</DOC><DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880920-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0655EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NASA-Young     09-20 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NASA-Young,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Chief Astronaut Disappointed With Space Program Progress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former chief astronaut says the emphasis on the
space shuttle is to blame for a slowdown in <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s space program.
   Astronaut <PERSON>John W. Young</PERSON>, who flew on the first manned Gemini
mission in <DATE>1965</DATE> and later walked on the moon, expressed
disappointment with the space program's progress in a recent
interview.
   ``It is almost 20 years since we landed people on the moon,''
said <PERSON>Young</PERSON>, 57. ``And if you had asked me after the moon landing
what we'd be doing in 20 years, I'd have said we'd have a base on
the moon in 20 years.''
   Young, now a safety and engineering trouble-shooter for <ORGANIZATION>Johnson
Space Center</ORGANIZATION>'s director, commanded the first and ninth shuttle
flights while serving as chief astronaut for the <ORGANIZATION>National
Aeronautics and Space Admininstration</ORGANIZATION>.
   He said the shuttles on which <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> staked its future in the
early <DATE>1970s</DATE> have never been the inexpensive, quickly refurbished
workhorses that their supporters promised.
   ``I never believed it could be that way,'' <PERSON>Young</PERSON> said. ``I
wasn't involved in selling it, but I was involved in the technical
details of helping design and build it, and it was too
complicated.''
   Young said the shuttle is capable of fulfilling its creators'
expectations, but tight budgets hurt it when <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> could not afford
to stockpile spare parts for quick repairs. And, he said, the
spacecraft's design can slow repairs because some areas are hard to
reach.
   He said that quick shuttle turnarounds and reflights and routine
<LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> landings never panned out, nor is the shuttle an
inexpensive way to fly.
   The basic assumption that it pays to salvage and reuse each <MONEY>$15
million</MONEY> solid-fuel rocket booster may be wrong, <PERSON>Young</PERSON> said.
   He also said the delays are affecting the supply of flight-ready
astronauts. Fourteen astronauts who flew before the <DATE>Jan. 28, 1986</DATE>,
Challenger explosion decided not to wait for flights to resume. The
space center has 93 astronauts and is accepting applications
through <DATE>July 1</DATE> for a <DATE>1990</DATE> astronaut class.
   ``I expect there's a lot of astronauts leaving because they see
the line at the end of the tunnel,'' <PERSON>Young</PERSON> said. ``The line they've
got to stand in to get a flight is so long.''
</TEXT>
