<HEAD>Neil Armstrong Took `Small Step' Himself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For nearly 20 years, space buffs have wondered
who composed the words ``That's one small step for a man'' which
<PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON> said when he stepped on the moon.
   Now, with the one-score anniversary coming up <DATE>July 20</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION>
says that not only were those words his own, but that he composed
them on the spot.
   <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION>, commander of the Apollo 11 moon mission, was reunited
with his two crew mates for a news conference <DATE>Friday</DATE> to satisfy
requests for interviews in connection with celebrations planned
across the world to mark the event.
   He was asked when exactly he decided on the words ``That's one
small step for a man, one giant leap for mankind,'' which he said
after climbing down the ladder on the lunar lander.
   ``It was a statement that was natural in the sense of the
time,'' <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> said. ``I thought about it after we got there.''
   With that he destroyed longstanding rumors in space circles that
some anonymous public relations genius, not <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION>, created
those words for history.
   <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION>, along with lunar module pilot <PERSON>Edwin</PERSON> ``Buzz'' <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON>
and command module pilot <PERSON>Michael Collins</PERSON>, fielded questions from
reporters with humor and self-deprecation for the niche they carved
in the annals of exploration.
   Here are some <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> comments:
   _On the use of robots to explore space _ a technique favored by
many scientists: ``Man can be amused and amazed, and a robot can be
neither.''
   _On leaving footprints on the moon that will remain undisturbed
for millennia: ``I had hoped that somebody goes up there some day
and cleans them up.''
   _On how their lives were changed by their adventure: ``Before
<DATE>1969</DATE>, press conferences were much smaller.''
   _On whether the Apollo moon program was a stunt of little value:
``Even if it was a bad idea, I'm glad we did it.''
   All three were asked what moment of their mission they would
choose to relive.
   Aldrin, who just published a book on <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s space program,
answered it would be the <DATE>last 10</DATE> seconds before they touched down
on the lunar surface and the first 10 seconds afterward.
   <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> said, ``I would pick a moment when I could look out
the window and see a full Earth.''
   And <PERSON>Collins</PERSON> said it would be the moment when he saw the lunar
module returning from the moon's surface against the background of
the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> floating in the black of space.
   In his view, he said, were both the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> with three billion
people and the moon ship with only two.
</TEXT>
