<SECOND>BC-Apollo-Harrowing Landing, Adv 16,1107</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`There Were Some Scary Things During That Descent'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Apollo-Footprints on Moon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: In 9th graf, bgn, `Immediately it ..., word `attitude' in quote
is cq. This is part of an eight-story package for use at will or on successful
Sundays in July.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several times in the final minutes
before man first touched down on the moon's surface, the astronauts
and ground controllers came close to aborting the attempt.
   ``There were some scary things during that descent,'' astronaut
<PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON> recalled later. ``Especially those computer alarms.''
   After separating from <PERSON>Mike Collins</PERSON> and the mother ship, <ORGANIZATION>Columbia</ORGANIZATION>,
<ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Buzz Aldrin</PERSON>, in the lunar module <LOCATION>Eagle</LOCATION>, swooped behind
the backside of the moon, out of radio contact with <ORGANIZATION>Mission Control</ORGANIZATION>
in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>.
   Armstrong fired the descent engine on the farside, 70 minutes
before the planned touchdown.
   Ground controllers did not know until <TIME>39 minutes later</TIME>, when
<ORGANIZATION>Eagle</ORGANIZATION> returned to radio range, whether the engine had fired
successfully to shift the astronauts into an orbital path whose low
point was just 9.8 miles above the surface.
   Once Eagle reached this closest approach, <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> had five
seconds to decide whether to ignite the descent engine again to drop
to the surface or to abort and initiate a rendezvous course to
<ORGANIZATION>Columbia</ORGANIZATION>.
   As the critical moment approached, <ORGANIZATION>Mission Control</ORGANIZATION> detected two
problems that could cause an abort.
   ``We were getting broken voice and telemetry communications,''
recalls <PERSON>Gene Kranz</PERSON>, the Apollo 11 flight director who today is
director of flight operations at the <ORGANIZATION>Johnson Space Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>.
   ``Immediately it flashed through my mind this basic ground rule
that I had to be sure that whatever happened, we had to have data
during this critical attempt at descent and landing,'' <PERSON>Kranz</PERSON> said.
``The data was broken, but the key stuff was there. And we were able
to improve it by making a minor change in the LM's attitude.''
   At the same time, <PERSON>Stephen Bales</PERSON>, the 26-year-old guidance officer
in the control center, detected the module ``was going toward the
moon about 15 miles an hour faster than the guidance computer
thought it was because some navigation errors had been introduced
into the system.
   ``Now 15 miles an hour doesn't sound like much, but we had an
abort limit that I was supposed to call that said if this thing grew
to 23 miles an hour, I had to stop the landing. I had to say no
go,'' <PERSON>Bales</PERSON> said.
   That much excess speed would have pushed Eagle outside the
previously photographed landing zone in the <ORGANIZATION>Sea of Tranquillity</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``We did not want them trying to land in unfamiliar territory,''
said <PERSON>Bales</PERSON>, who today is chief of the systems division at the
<ORGANIZATION>Johnson Space Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>. Fortunately, the spacecraft did not
gain additional speed.
   These problems resolved, <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> was given the green light to
again start the descent engine. He pressed the button. Landing on
the <ORGANIZATION>Sea of Tranquillity</ORGANIZATION> was 12 minutes away.
   Suddenly, computer alarm lights began flashing in the cabin. The
guidance computer was overtaxed, and <ORGANIZATION>Eagle</ORGANIZATION> again was rapidly
approaching an abort situation.
   ``The computer was on a fixed one-second cycle,'' <PERSON>Bales</PERSON> said.
``It had to navigate, it had to guide, it had to display data to the
crew, it had to trim the engine. And if it couldn't get all its jobs
done in one second, it gave this overload alarm.
   ``Fortunately, the guys who programmed it were very sharp and
they put the least needed tasks at the bottom of the stack and the
most needed at the top,'' he said. ``We had seen the same thing in a
simulator run just two weeks before the launch. And because I could
see the computer was solving all the right problems, I told <PERSON>Gene
Kranz</PERSON> to have the crew ignore the alarms and keep going.''
   <PERSON>Chris Kraft</PERSON>, the flight operations director who now is a private
aerospace consultant, said in a recent interview that <PERSON>Bales</PERSON>'
contribution was ``absolutely vital.''
   ``Without his ability to see into the operations of that
computer, we would have waved off, aborted,'' <PERSON>Kraft</PERSON> said.
   Another abort situation faced <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> as they neared
the surface. Because of the navigation error, they were coming in
about four miles west of their planned touchdown point. Instead of
the relatively smooth area they'd expected, <ORGANIZATION>Eagle</ORGANIZATION> was coming down in
an area strewn with boulders and pocked with craters.
   Armstrong took manual control and began flying the module like a
helicopter, searching for a smooth spot.
   ``We didn't know what was going on,'' <PERSON>Bales</PERSON> said. ``We knew he
was close to the surface but was not landing. He was running out of
gas, and I said ... we're going to have to abort for gas.''
   Armstrong had only about 12 seconds of fuel left when he dropped
Eagle onto the surface.
   ``<LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Tranquillity Base</ORGANIZATION> here. The Eagle has landed,''
<ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> reported.
   ``<PERSON>Roger</PERSON>, Tranquillity,'' said astronaut <PERSON>Charlie Duke</PERSON>, the capsule
communicator in the control center. ``We copy you on the ground. You
got a bunch of guys about to turn blue. We're breathing again.''
   Everyone in the control center was cheering, applauding. Flight
director <PERSON>Kranz</PERSON> suddenly realized discipline was breaking down, that
the team had to be ready to make split-second decisions in case the
astronauts had to make a sudden takeoff from the moon.
   ``All right, everyone,'' he said. ``Get settled down. There's a
lot of work to do.''
   Within seconds, they were preparing for a possible emergency
liftoff.
   Radio data indicated pressure in a descent engine fuel line,
apparently because it was frozen.
   ``That started sounding pretty bad,'' <PERSON>Bales</PERSON> recalled. ``Gene
called down to me and said, `I don't have time to follow what you're
doing because I've got to follow this freezing problem. You just
make sure you've got all the right stuff loaded into the computer
because we may be lifting off.' That really bothered me because it
would be a shame if we had to lift off now.
   ``As we were loading the right insertion velocity, azimuth and
other things into the LM computer, the line that they were talking
about ruptured,'' <PERSON>Bales</PERSON> said. ``It caused no damage and because it
was on the no-longer-needed descent engine, everything was OK. That
was a big, big, big relief. They stayed on the moon.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 16</NOTE>
