<HEAD>Astronauts Remember Historic Apollo 8 Mission 20 Years Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the three Apollo 8 astronauts reminisced
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE> about their mission around the <DATE>moon 20 years ago this month</DATE>
_ a feat they said helped lift the nation out of despair at a trying
time in its history.
   ``You have to remember the time span of when Apollo 8 went up,
which was the end of <DATE>1968</DATE> ... not a very stellar year here in this
country,'' <PERSON>James Lovell</PERSON>, who served as command module pilot,
recalled at the <ORGANIZATION>Museum of Science and Industry</ORGANIZATION>. The spacecraft's
command module is on loan there from the <ORGANIZATION>National Air and Space
Museum</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   ``<PERSON>Bobby Kennedy</PERSON> was assasinated, <PERSON>Martin Luther King</PERSON> ... the
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> war was going on, the Democrtaic convention in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> ...
we had all sorts of riots _ and it was sort of a down year,'' <PERSON>Lovell</PERSON>
added.
   ``It was some sort of project or an achievement that everybody
could look up to ... it was a goal that you could go outside and see
the moon and know that the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> had finally put a
spacecraft around the moon ...
   ``It couldn't have happened at a better time,'' he said.
   Joining <PERSON>Lovell</PERSON> at the museum was <PERSON>Frank Borman</PERSON>, the Apollo 8
commander. The third astronaut on the mission was <PERSON>William Anders</PERSON>.
   Apollo 8 is perhaps best remembered for footage broadcast
internationally of the three astronauts reading passages from the
biblical book of Genesis on Christmas Eve <DATE>1968</DATE>, with a stunning view
of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> from 250,000 miles away.
   ``Up to that point it was the largest audience that had ever
listened to a human voice,'' <PERSON>Lovell</PERSON> recalled
   The mission, launched <DATE>Dec. 21, 1968</DATE>, hurled the three astronauts
25,000 miles an hour, a speed no human had endured. During the
six-day space flight _ then the longest on record _ the men circled
the moon 10 times, photographing potential sites for future Apollo
landings there.
   The Apollo 11 mission _ the first to put a man on the moon _
landed <DATE>six months later</DATE>, on <DATE>July 20, 1969</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Borman</PERSON> recalled the Apollo program as generating ``almost a
nationalistic fervor'' that faded as space flights became blase.
   <PERSON>Borman</PERSON>, 60, left the space program in <DATE>1970</DATE> and took the helm at
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, where he served as chairman for 11 years until his
resignation in <DATE>1986</DATE>. He currently serves as vice chairman at <ORGANIZATION>Texas
Air</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Lovell</PERSON>, also 60, resigned from the space program in <DATE>1973</DATE> and
currently serves as executive vice president at <ORGANIZATION>Centel Business
Systems</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>.
   ``Apollo 8, I think, will always be the single most highlight of
my professional life,'' <PERSON>Borman</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
