<HEAD>Amrstrong, Aldrin Help NASA Celebrate 20th Anniversary of Apollo
11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Neil A. Armstrong</PERSON> and <PERSON>Edwin E.</PERSON> ``Buzz'' <PERSON>Aldrin
Jr.</PERSON> thanked <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s rocket fuel researchers <DATE>Thursday</DATE> night during a
celebration marking this month's 20th anniversary of the first
manned landing on the moon.
   ``We were participants and witness to the birth of a new human
era,'' <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> said in brief remarks to several hundred people at
the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Lewis Research
Center</ORGANIZATION>, which helped develop rocket fuel for the Apollo 11 flight.
   <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION>, commander of the three-man Apollo 11 crew, and <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON>
said present and past researchers at the center had been
instrumental in helping them accomplish the first manned lunar
landing on <DATE>July 20, 1969</DATE>.
   ``Their contributions were of critical importance to our
success,'' <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Aldrin, who followed <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> out of the Eagle landing craft
onto the moon's surface, said he has expected for more than a year
that the 20th anniversary of the Apollo 11 landing would have
special meaning.
   ``I sense that the 20th anniversary is going to mean a lot for
this nation,'' said <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON>, who said it was unfortunate that the
nation hasn't sent a manned craft to the moon since Apollo 17 in
<DATE>1972</DATE>.
   Aldrin called for development of a space port which would serve
as a stopover point in space using different types of transportation.
</TEXT>
