<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Armstrong, Collins Withstood Pressure; Aldrin Not So Lucky</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Part of an eight-story package for use at will or on successful
Sundays in July.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON>, the first man on the
moon, withstood the pressure of fame. <PERSON>Buzz Aldrin</PERSON>, the second
moon-walker, was not so lucky.
   After they returned to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> as heroes, along with pilot <PERSON>Michael
Collins</PERSON> who had stayed in lunar orbit, there were months of public
appearances, goodwill visits abroad and seemingly endless interviews
and autograph signing.
   The three Apollo 11 crewmen remained with <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> for awhile.
   In <DATE>1971</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION> retreated to the privacy he craved. He also
realized a dream to teach, becoming a professor of aerospace
engineering at the <ORGANIZATION>University of Cincinnati</ORGANIZATION>.
   After nine years at the university he became an aerospace
consultant. Today he is chairman of <ORGANIZATION>CTA Inc.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>, a
computer systems company. Now 58, he and his wife, <PERSON>Jan</PERSON>, live on a
farm near <LOCATION>Lebanon</LOCATION>.
   Aldrin had trouble handling the post-Apollo 11 celebrations and
subsequent disappointments when he returned to active military duty
with the <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``My depression was brought on by being thrust into the
uncomfortable area of public relations, followed by a period of
wondering where you fit in after being an astronaut on the moon,''
<PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> said.
   An <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> colonel, in <DATE>1971</DATE> he was named commander of the
<ORGANIZATION>Aerospace Research Pilots School</ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION>Edwards Air Force Base</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION> _
``a school I didn't know anything about'' after being away from the
service 10 years. He said his previous military training had not
prepared him to be a leader.
   Eight months later, <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> checked into a military hospital in
<LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>. ``I was on my way to having a good old-fashioned
American nervous breakdown. I realized it and asked for help.''
   He went through bouts with mental illness and alcoholism but
recovered from and lectured on both. During this bad period he was
divorced, remarried and divorced again. He wrote a book, ``Return to
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>,'' about those troubled times.
   After his recovery he retired from the <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> and became an
aerospace consultant. Today, at 59, he has remarried and is
president of his own Los Angeles-based firm, <ORGANIZATION>Research &amp; Engineering</ORGANIZATION>.
He is author of a recently published book about his Apollo 11
experience, ``Men From Earth.''
   Collins left <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>January 1970</DATE> to become assistant secretary
of state for public affairs. A year later he joined the <ORGANIZATION>Smithsonian</ORGANIZATION>
Institution as director of the <ORGANIZATION>National Air and Space Museum</ORGANIZATION>,
overseeing the building of the museum, which opened in <DATE>1976</DATE>.
   In <DATE>1980</DATE>, <PERSON>Collins</PERSON> became vice president of the <ORGANIZATION>Vought Corporation</ORGANIZATION>,
and in <DATE>1985</DATE> be became president of his own company, <ORGANIZATION>Michael Collins
Associates</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, where he and wife Pat live.
   ``I'm trying to make a living as a writer,'' <PERSON>Collins</PERSON>, 58, said
recently. He has written ``Carrying the Fire'' and ``Liftoff,'' two
highly acclaimed books about the space program. ``I'm currently
writing a book on Mars.''
</TEXT>
