<HEAD>Moon Landing Coverage Replayed at Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space buff who wants to relive the night
<PERSON>Neil Armstrong</PERSON> and <PERSON>Buzz Aldrin</PERSON> first walked on the moon can do so
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> at the <ORGANIZATION>National Air and Space Museum</ORGANIZATION>.
   In the same building where the Apollo 11 command module is
displayed, the original television coverage of the moon landing will
be replayed <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the 20th anniversary of the event.
   It will be timed to the actual event, including <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION>'s ``one
small step for a man, one giant leap for mankind'' statement at
<TIME>10:56 p.m</TIME>. The show runs from <TIME>7:30 p.m.</TIME> to <TIME>1:30 a.m.</TIME>
   <DATE>Earlier Thursday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Armstrong</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Aldrin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Michael Collins</PERSON>, who
orbited in the command module, will join President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> for a
ceremony on the steps of the museum.
   The 3,700 journalists who covered the historic flight have been
invited, along with 46 astronauts, to attend a <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> party
at the <ORGANIZATION>National Press Club</ORGANIZATION>.
